<subSubSection pageId="51" pageNumber="52" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="51.[151,1437,1468,1817]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
<materialsCitation ID-GBIF-Occurrence="1835975966" country="Jordan" location="Jordan" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" specimenCount="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,300,1468,1493]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Habitat:</emphasis>
The Libyan jird is common all over the Syrian Desert; sharing its habitat with related species. It is known in Wādī ‘Araba and southern 
<collectingCountry box="[596,674,1504,1529]" name="Jordan" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Jordan</collectingCountry>
. Colonies are constructed in hard soil with abundant vegetation. Burrows are very complex and consist of many openings, nest and food chambers. Atallah (1977) reported that it feeds 
<collectedFrom box="[219,493,1576,1601]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
on 
<taxonomicName box="[257,493,1576,1601]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cucurbitaceae" genus="Citrullus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Cucurbitales" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="coloycnthis">
<emphasis box="[257,493,1576,1601]" italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Citrullus coloycnthis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</collectedFrom>
, a common desert annual plant. This is a diurnal species, however, it may appear during the night.
</materialsCitation>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="51" pageNumber="52" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="51.[151,1437,1468,1817]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,289,1648,1673]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Biology</emphasis>
: The Libyan jird is reported to be solitary in some areas, but to form small colonies in others as in Jordan. Females give birth to 2–4 young (Osborn &amp; Helmy, 1980).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="51" pageNumber="52" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="51.[151,1437,1468,1817]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,317,1720,1745]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Remarks:</emphasis>
This is a common species with a wide range of distribution in the arid regions of 
<collectingCountry box="[1300,1378,1720,1745]" name="Jordan" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Jordan</collectingCountry>
. The karyotype from specimens collected from the Jordanian eastern desert (referred to as “ 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Duvernoy" baseAuthorityYear="1842" box="[1112,1213,1756,1781]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Meriones" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="shawi">
<emphasis box="[1112,1213,1756,1781]" italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">M. shawi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
”) yeiled 2n=44 and FN=74 (Qumsiyeh 
<emphasis box="[369,418,1792,1817]" italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">et al</emphasis>
., 1986).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
